caption: Figure 1: Comparisons of of DPSet, ALP, and DP Count Sketch with δ < 2-40. The x-axis is privacy parameter e and the y-axis is error probability, encoding time (ms) or decoding time (ms).
description: This figure compares the performance of three differentially private set mechanisms: DPSet (the proposed method), ALP, and DP Count Sketch.  It shows the trade-off between privacy (epsilon, the x-axis) and utility (error probability, encoding time, and decoding time, the y-axis).  The results are presented for three different set sizes (k = 2<sup>12</sup>, 2<sup>16</sup>, 2<sup>20</sup>) and demonstrate DPSet's superior utility across all metrics, particularly in terms of significantly lower error probability than competing methods.

caption: Figure 1: Comparisons of of DPSet, ALP, and DP Count Sketch with δ < 2⁻⁴⁰. The x-axis is privacy parameter ε and the y-axis is error probability, encoding time (ms) or decoding time (ms).
description: This figure compares the performance of three different differentially private set mechanisms: DPSet (the authors' proposed method), ALP, and DP Count Sketch.  It shows three sets of graphs: one for error probability, one for encoding time, and one for decoding time.  Each set of graphs is broken down by the size of the input set (k = 2¹², 2¹⁶, 2²⁰). The x-axis represents the privacy parameter ε, which controls the privacy-utility trade-off, and the y-axis shows either the error probability, encoding time in milliseconds, or decoding time in milliseconds. The figure demonstrates that DPSet generally achieves lower error probability and comparable or faster encoding/decoding times compared to ALP and DP Count Sketch, especially as the input set size grows.
